# The build context is uploaded to the daemon on every build. Keeping it small is
# not tidiness — it is the difference between a one-second and a ten-second
# no-op rebuild, and it stops a stray `data/` directory from ending up in a layer.
#
# `.git` is excluded, and that is a decision rather than an oversight. The Go
# toolchain can stamp vcs.revision and vcs.modified into a binary built inside a
# work tree (internal/buildinfo reads them), but only if a `git` binary is on the
# builder's PATH — and golang:alpine ships without one. With `-buildvcs=auto`,
# the default, the toolchain then skips the stamp *silently*, so keeping .git in
# the context would upload tens of megabytes to buy nothing. The Dockerfile passes
# -buildvcs=false to say so out loud, and the version comes from --build-arg,
# which the Makefile, the CI workflow and GoReleaser all supply.

.git/
/bin/
/dist/
/data/
/.cache/
/.bench/
/.prof/

# Build outputs and local artefacts.
/server
/agent
*.test
*.out
coverage.out
coverage.html

# Rendered manifests and charts are inputs to Kubernetes, never to a Go build.
/deploy/k8s/
/deploy/charts/

# Documentation. A README change should not invalidate the builder layer.
/docs/
**/*.md

.DS_Store
.github/
